  <subsection xml:id="subsec-double-angle-advanced-examples">
    <title>Advanced Examples</title>
    
    <exercise>
      <title>Geometric Mean</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the geometric mean of <m>\sin^2\theta</m> and <m>\cos^2\theta</m>, in terms of sine only. Note: the geometric mean of two numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is <m>\sqrt{ab}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p><m>\frac{1}{2} \abs{\sin{(2\theta)}}</m>.</p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    
    <exercise>
      <title>Exact Value in Terms of Variables</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Given that <m>\cos\theta=\frac{a}{x}</m> and <m>\theta</m> is in quadrant 4, find the exact value of <m>\sin 2\theta</m> in terms of <m>a</m> and <m>x</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p><m>\sin 2\theta=2\sin\theta\cos\theta</m>.</p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>\sin 2\theta=-\frac{2a\sqrt{x^2-a^2}}{x^2}</m>.</p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    
    <exercise>
      <title>Expression for Tangent</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Given that <m>\csc\theta=\frac{b}{x}</m> and <m>\theta</m> is in quadrant <m>2</m>, find an expression for <m>\tan 2\theta</m> in terms of <m>b</m> and <m>x</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p><m>\tan 2\theta=\frac{2\tan\theta}{1-\tan^2\theta}</m>, and simplify the complex fraction.</p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>\tan 2\theta=-\frac{2x\sqrt{b^2-x^2}}{b^2-2x^2}</m>.</p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    
    <exercise>
      <title>Solving with Tangent</title>
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>\sin{x} = -2 \cos{x}</m> and <m>\frac{\pi}{2} \leq x \leq \pi</m>, find <m>\tan{(2x)}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>to find <m>\tan{x}</m>, divide both sides of the equation by <m>\cos{x}</m>.</p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>\frac{4}{3}</m>.</p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-proofs-double-angle-identities">
    <title>Proofs of Double-Angle Identities</title>
    <p>
      The double-angle identities are derived from the sum and difference identities, by adding the same angle <m>\theta</m> to itself.
    </p>
    
    <proof>
      <p>Using the sum and difference identities, for <m>\sin{(2\theta)}</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin{(2\theta)} \amp = \sin{(\theta + \theta)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \sin{\theta}\cos{\theta} + \cos{\theta}\sin{\theta} \amp\amp \text{by the sine sum identity}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\sin{\theta}\cos{\theta} \amp\amp \text{simplify}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>For <m>\cos{(2\theta)}</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos{(2\theta)} \amp = \cos{(\theta + \theta)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \cos{\theta}\cos{\theta} - \sin{\theta}\sin{\theta} \amp\amp \text{by the cosine sum identity}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \cos^2{\theta} - \sin^2{\theta} \amp\amp \text{simplify}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Then, for the 2nd form of the cosine identity, use the Pythagorean identity,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos{(2\theta)} \amp = \cos^2{\theta} - \sin^2{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (1 - \sin^2{\theta}) - \sin^2{\theta} \amp\amp \text{by the Pythagorean identity}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 1 - 2\sin^2{\theta} \amp\amp \text{simplify}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>And, for the 3rd form,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos{(2\theta)} \amp = \cos^2{\theta} - (1 - \cos^2{\theta}) \amp\amp \text{by the Pythagorean identity}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\cos^2{\theta} - 1 \amp\amp \text{simplify}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Also, for <m>\tan{(2\theta)}</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\tan{(2\theta)} \amp = \tan{(\theta + \theta)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\tan{\theta} + \tan{\theta}}{1 - \tan{\theta}\tan{\theta}} \amp\amp \text{by the tangent sum identity}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{2\tan{\theta}}{1 - \tan^2{\theta}} \amp\amp \text{simplify}</mrow>
      </md>
    </proof>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-triple-angle-identities">
    <title>Triple-Angle Identities</title>
    <p>
      We can also find expressions for <m>\sin{(3\theta)}</m> and <m>\cos{(3\theta)}</m> in terms of their associated single angles, using the sum and difference identities and the double-angle identities. In other words, triple-angle identities.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Deriving the Cosine Triple-Angle Identity</title>
      <p>To find <m>\cos{(3x)}</m>, we can think of <m>3x</m> as <m>2x + x</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos{(3x)} \amp = \cos{(2x + x)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \cos{(2x)} \cos{x} - \sin{(2x)} \sin{x}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Here, there are <m>\cos{(2x)}</m> and <m>\sin{(2x)}</m>. For <m>\sin{(2x)}</m>, we have <m>\sin{(2x)} = 2 \sin{x} \cos{x}</m>. For <m>\cos{(2x)}</m>, there are 3 options, and we will choose <m>\cos{(2x)} = 2\cos^2{x} - 1</m>, because we want the final expression to be in terms of cosine only.</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = \underbrace{\brac{2\cos^2{x} - 1}} \cos{x} - \underbrace{2 \sin{x} \cos{x}} \cdot \sin{x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\cos^3{x} - \cos{x} - 2 \sin^2{x} \cos{x}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>We will replace <m>\sin^2{x} = 1 - \cos^2{x}</m>, again because we want everything in terms of cosine only,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\cos^3{x} - \cos{x} - 2 \brac{1 - \cos^2{x}} \cos{x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\cos^3{x} - \cos{x} - 2 \cos{x} + 2 \cos^3{x} \amp\amp \text{distributing}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 4\cos^3{x} - 3 \cos{x} \amp\amp \text{collecting like terms}</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      In summary,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\boxed{\cos{(3\theta)} = 4\cos^3{\theta} - 3 \cos{\theta}}</mrow>
    </md>
    
    <p>
      Similarly, you can find that,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\boxed{\sin{(3\theta)} = 3\sin{\theta} - 4 \sin^3{\theta}}</mrow>
    </md>
    
    <example>
      <title>Prove the identity <m>\sin{(3\theta)} = 3\sin{\theta} - 4 \sin^3{\theta}</m></title>
      <p>Solution: We again think of <m>3x</m> as <m>2x + x</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin(3x) \amp = \sin(2x + x)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \sin(2x)\cos x + \cos(2x)\sin x</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Here, there are <m>\sin(2x)</m> and <m>\cos(2x)</m>. For <m>\sin(2x)</m>, we have <m>\sin(2x) = 2\sin x \cos x</m>. For <m>\cos(2x)</m>, there are 3 options, and we will choose <m>\cos(2x) = 1 - 2\sin^2 x</m>, because we want the final expression to be in terms of sine only.</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = \underbrace{2\sin x \cos x}\cos x + \underbrace{(1 - 2\sin^2 x)}\sin x</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\sin x \cos^2 x + \sin x - 2\sin^3 x</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>We will replace <m>\cos^2 x = 1 - \sin^2 x</m>, again because we want everything in terms of sine only,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\sin x (1 - \sin^2 x) + \sin x - 2\sin^3 x</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2\sin x - 2\sin^3 x + \sin x - 2\sin^3 x \amp\amp \text{distributing}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 3\sin x - 4\sin^3 x \amp\amp \text{collecting like terms}</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      Similarly, we can find a tangent triple-angle identity,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\boxed{\tan{(3\theta)} = \frac{3\tan{\theta} - \tan^3{\theta}}{1 - 3 \tan^2{\theta}}}</mrow>
    </md>
    
    <example>
      <title>Prove the identity <m>\tan{(3\theta)} = \frac{3\tan{\theta} - \tan^3{\theta}}{1 - 3 \tan^2{\theta}}</m></title>
      <p>Solution: We again think of <m>3x</m> as <m>2x + x</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\tan(3x) \amp = \tan(2x + x)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\tan(2x) + \tan x}{1 - \tan(2x)\tan x}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Here, there is <m>\tan(2x)</m>. For <m>\tan(2x)</m> we have the double-angle identity</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\tan(2x) = \frac{2\tan x}{1 - \tan^2 x}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Then,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\tan{(3x)} \amp = \frac{\frac{2\tan x}{1 - \tan^2 x} + \tan x}{1 - \frac{2\tan x}{1 - \tan^2 x}\cdot \tan x}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>To simplify this complex fraction, clear denominators by multiplying the numerator and denominator by <m>1-\tan^2{x}</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\tan(3x) \amp = \frac{\frac{2\tan x}{1 - \tan^2 x} + \tan x}{1 - \frac{2\tan x}{1 - \tan^2 x}\cdot \tan x} \cdot \frac{1-\tan^2{x}}{1-\tan^2{x}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{2\tan x + \tan x(1 - \tan^2 x)}{(1 - \tan^2 x) - 2\tan^2 x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{2\tan x + \tan x - \tan^3 x}{1 - \tan^2 x - 2\tan^2 x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\tan{(3x)} \amp = \frac{3\tan x - \tan^3 x}{1 - 3\tan^2 x}</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  
</section>